Each die contributes to a, b, c as follows: - (0,0,0): 1 way - (1,0,0): 1 way - (0,1,0): 1 way - (2,0,0): 1 way - (0,0,1): 1 way - (1,1,0): 1 way Therefore, each die has 6 possible contributions, each contributing a unique vector. This is similar to the problem of counting the number of distinct subset sums, but with six possible elements each with their own weights. The number of distinct sums can be calculated using dynamic programming. Lets model this as a dynamic programming problem where we track the number of ways to reach each possible exponent triplet (a, b, c) after n dice. The state space is the number of possible (a, b, c) triplets, which is roughly O(n^3), but many states are not reachable. However, since n is not too large, we can compute this incrementally. Lets denote dp[n][a][b][c] as the number of ways to have exponents (a, b, c) after n dice. The recurrence relation is: dp[n][a][b][c] = dp[n-1][a][b][c] + dp[n-1][a-1][b][c] + dp[n-1][a][b-1][c] + dp[n-1][a-2][b][c] + dp[n-1][a][b][c-1] + dp[n-1][a-1][b-1][c] With the base case dp[0][0][0][0] = 1, and dp[0][a][b][c] = 0 otherwise.
